<subSubSection id="6D837C851038FFA7DBE2FBCC4EE72E20" pageId="29" pageNumber="130" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="25262F0E1038FFA7DBE2FBCC4EE72E20" blockId="29.[151,1437,655,1293]" pageId="29" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1038FFA7DBE2FBCC4D0E2F8C" bold="true" box="[199,315,1159,1185]" pageId="29" pageNumber="130">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1038FFA7DA67FBCC4D9D2F8C" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[322,424,1159,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setifer">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1038FFA7DA67FBCC4D9D2F8C" box="[322,424,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="130">A. setifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1038FFA7D951FBCC4ED12F8C" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[628,740,1159,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1038FFA7D951FBCC4ED12F8C" box="[628,740,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="130">A. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="5D8E6F9E1038FFA7D80DFBCC4FB92F8C" box="[808,908,1159,1185]" name="Thailand" pageId="29" pageNumber="130">Thailand</collectingCountry>
in appearance, but these two species are easily distinguished by above description and the key, and possibly they are not so closely related. The character states of the antennal chaetotaxy and the fusion of mesopresternum and mesoeusternum of 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1038FFA7DF77FB84488D2FC4" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[1106,1208,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setifer">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1038FFA7DF77FB84488D2FC4" box="[1106,1208,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="130">A. setifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are rather similar to those of 
